<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[146,770,1825,1932]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[146,244,1854,1873]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Discussion</emphasis>
. This species appears to be associated with lowland tropical forests in Borneo and 
<collectingRegion box="[388,465,1884,1903]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Archer" box="[478,594,1883,1903]" firstAuthor="Archer" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="43 - 50" refId="ref11948" refString="Archer, M. E. 1999. Taxonomy, distribution and nesting biology of Vespa binghami, V. basalis, V. variabilis, V. fervida, V. luctuosa, V. multimaculata and V. bellicosa. Entomol. Monthly Mag. 135: 43 - 50." type="journal article" year="1999">Archer 1999</bibRefCitation>
). It is unlikely that it would become invasive in other regions. It has very distinctive
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[818,1442,1473,1522]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
black and yellow banding on the thorax and metasoma. It is not known where 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Saussure" authorityYear="1854" box="[949,1053,1502,1521]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Vespa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bellicosa">
<emphasis box="[949,1053,1502,1521]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">V. bellicosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
build their nests.
</paragraph>
